Justification:  
The condition C11 requires that for every minimal semantic basis of the claim, there exists at least one P-type argument whose justification contains that basis. Here, the claim is "Elisa understands brain functions." The P-type arguments provide justifications that rely on indirect inferences (e.g., from innovative research, gaining insights, or motivation), but none of them directly or fully contain a minimal semantic basis that would definitively support the claim. Moreover, the S-type arguments highlight contradictions and missing evidence (e.g., lack of international recognition, inconsistency with solving complex problems), which undermine the completeness of the P-type justifications. Since not all minimal semantic bases are covered by the P-type arguments, C11 is not satisfied.